    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p>Previously placed in family Romancheinidae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_5089",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Colony consists of a thin, flat, pale white-to-grey, more-or-less circular encrustation composed of radiating rows of zooecia.</p><p>When examined closely the individual zooecia have flat, irregularly-arranged, oval cases. The distal openings to these are wide and oval with a raised edge and the convex surface is punctured by large, conspicuous pores.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_5090",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Individual zooecia less than 1 mm long, colonies typically 2-5 cm across.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_5091",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Probably endemic to South Africa (reports from Australia on WoRMS probably another species).</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Cape Town to KwaZulu-Natal.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_5092",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Common on the undersides of boulders in the intertidal and shallow subtidal and on mussel shells to a depth of 20 m.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_5093",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>All bryozoans are filter-feeders. The feeding zooids extend when undisturbed and the tentacles, which are lined with cilia, are expanded, forming a bell-shaped funnel. Beating of the cilia directs food particles down into the funnel and to the mouth, where they are ingested.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_5094",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Existing colonies expand by budding new zooecia around the margins. New colonies are established by sexual reproduction. Fertilized eggs are released into the water column, where they undertake a short larval life before finding a suitable habitat and metamorphosing into the adult form.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_5095",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>One of several pale, encrusting species found on the undersides of boulders, such as <i>Steginoporella buskii</i>, but has much more distinctive, larger pores on zooids. Definitive identification requires microscopic examination of zooecia ornamentation.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_5096",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa (Fourth edition). Struik Nature, Cape Town (p. 136).<br><br>Florence, WK (2016). Some deep-water cheilostome Bryozoa from the south coast of South Africa. <i>African Natural History</i>, 12, 5-11.<br><br>Florence, WK, Hayward, PJ & Gibbons, MJ (2007). Taxonomy of shallow-water Bryozoa from the west coast of South Africa. <i>African Natural History</i>, 3(1), 1-58. (p. 35).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_5097",
